Swift&#x27;s Optional is just Maybe with some built-in sugar. Sum types are supported, with the caveat that the compiler is sort of broken when it comes to generics.<p>Personally, I just want higher-kinded types, and for the following code snippets to work as-is:<p><pre><code>  enum Either<A,B> {
    case Left(A)
    case Right(B)
  }

  enum Tree<A> {
    case Leaf
    case Node(Tree<A>, A, Tree<A>)
  }
</code></pre>
The first breaks because of the &quot;Unimplemented non-fixed multi-payload enum layout&quot; compiler error, and the second breaks because enums have value semantics. Both can be worked around in full generality by declaring a &#x27;Box<T>&#x27; generic wrapper class, but that workaround is inelegant and cumbersome.
